Acer, AU Optronics, EVA Airways, Tripod: Taiwan Stocks Preview

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-06-28T00:29:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-28/acer-au-optronics-eva-airways-tripod-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The Taiex Index fell 32.67, or 0.4 percent, to 8,500.16.  Tourism-related: Taiwan will allow individual Chinese
visitors to travel to the island today, the first time in more
than six decades.  China Airlines Ltd. (2610)  (2610 TT), Taiwan’s largest carrier,
gained 3.7 percent to NT$19.75.  EVA Airways Corp. (2618)  (2618 TT), the
second-biggest, advanced 0.7 percent to NT$29.20.  Formosa
International Hotels Corp. (2707)  (2707 TT) increased 1.1 percent to
NT$552.  Acer Inc. (2353)  (2353 TT): The world’s second-largest laptop
maker won a Bangkok Metropolitan Authority tender to provide
personal computers, servers, educational software and networking
solutions to schools in the city, the Taipei-based company said
in an e-mailed statement yesterday. The company didn’t state the
value of the order. The stock dropped 1.3 percent to NT$47.35.  AU Optronics Corp. (2409)  (2409 TT): Taiwan’s second-largest maker
of liquid-crystal displays sued Samsung Electronics Co. and AT&T
Inc., accusing them of infringing some of its display patents.
John Lucas, a U.S.-based spokesman for Suwon, South Korea-based
Samsung, and  Mark Siegel , a spokesman for Dallas-based AT&T,
both declined to comment on the suit. The stock retreated 1.8
percent to NT$19.40.  Chimei Innolux Corp. (3481)  (3481 TT): Taiwan’s biggest flat panel
maker was told by a U.S. jury to pay $15 million to Mondis
Technology Ltd. for infringing the company’s patents. The stock
lost 2.7 percent to NT$21.60.  Tripod Technology Corp. (3044)  (3044 TT): The printed circuit
board maker was raised to “neutral” from “underweight” at
HSBC Holdings Plc by equity analyst Tse-Yong Yao. The brokerage
has a share-price estimate of NT$122. The stock gained 2.2
percent to NT$118.50.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Weiyi Lim in Singapore at 
